President Donald J. Trump has announced his intent to nominate two judicial nominees. Ada E. Brown of Texas is nominated to serve as District Judge on the U.S. District Court for the Northern District of Texas. Brown is currently a Justice on Texas' Fifth Court of Appeals and previously practiced at McKool Smith, focusing on commercial litigation and patent infringement matters. She has also served as a judge on the Dallas County Criminal Court and as a prosecutor in the Dallas County District Attorney's Office. Brown received her J.D. from Emory University School of Law and her B.A., magna cum laude, from Spelman College.

David John Novak of Virginia is nominated to serve as District Judge on the U.S. District Court for the Eastern District of Virginia. Novak is currently a Magistrate Judge on the U.S. District Court for the Eastern District of Virginia and also serves as an Adjunct Professor at the University of Richmond School of Law and the William & Mary Law School, teaching a course on national security law. He has previously served as an Assistant U.S. Attorney in the Eastern District of Virginia, including as Chief of the Criminal Division and Senior Litigation Counsel. Novak received his J.D. from Villanova University School of Law and his B.A., magna cum laude, from St. Vincent College.